 the protests and in some cases were preparing to go with weapons,\" said Brian Fishman, Facebook's director of counterterrorism and dangerous organizations policy. \u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>The company did not divulge details of the account users — such as their specific plans for protests or where in the U.S. they live. It said “approximately” 190 accounts were removed overall.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>Both the Proud Boys and American Guard had been banned from Facebook for violating rules prohibiting hate speech. Facebook said it will continue to remove new pages, groups or accounts created by users trying to circumvent the ban.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>Earlier this week, Facebook announced the removal of a “handful” of other accounts created by white supremacists who had been posing on Twitter as members of the far-left antifa movement.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>Facebook announced two other actions on Friday to root out networks of fake accounts used in attempts to manipulate public opinion in Africa and Iraq:\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>— Hundreds of fake Instagram and Facebook accounts created in Tunisia in an alleged effort to influence elections in that country and other French-speaking nations in sub-Saharan Africa: \u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>The accounts and related pages were used to impersonate local citizens, politicians and news organizations. More than 3.8 million accounts followed one or more of the pages, and more than 171,000 people had followed one of the fake Instagram accounts.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>The network of fake accounts and pages was uncovered by the Atlantic Council's Digital Forensic Research Lab. In their \u003ca href=\"https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/in-depth-research-reports/operation-carthage:-how-a-tunisian-company-conducted-influence-operations-in-african-presidential-elections/\">report\u003c/a>, researchers at the DFRL said they've noticed more and more PR firms dabbling in misinformation and online manipulation.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>— Facebook also deactivated another network of 102 fake Instagram and Facebook accounts used to impersonate local politicians and news organizations in the Kurdish region in northern Iraq. Company officials said the fake accounts, which appeared to target domestic audiences in Kurdistan, were linked to Kurdish intelligence services.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>","mediaCount":1,"shortId":"91c1868557ba6e88e32b2607b26724d6","localLinkUrl":"https://apnews.com/91c1868557ba6e88e32b2607b26724d6","interactiveLinkUrl":null,"downloadSettings":null,"interactiveLinkUrlText":null,"richEmbeds":[],"id":"urn:publicid:ap.org:91c1868557ba6e88e32b2607b26724d6","media":[],"videoContext":"created by users trying to circumvent the ban.\u003c/p>","tagIds":["apf-technology","Media","apf-GeneralNews","Socialmedia","apf-business","Hategroups","AmericanProtests","apf-usnews","APFactCheck"],"hasTextOverlay":false,"bylines":"By DAVID KLEPPER","leadPhotoId":"fa035260af0f4ff0a27e0259769579aa"}],"notificationUrl":null,"textColor":"#000000","sponsorUrl":null,"teamLimit":null,"cardType":"Wire Story","sponsorServeAd":false,"notificationText":null,"notificationUpdated":null},{"feed":[],"pollUpdated":null,"headlineWidget":false,"dividerColor":null,"tagObjs":[],"sponsorImageUrl":null,"hubPeekLinkText":null,"borderColor":null,"cardTitle":null,"localMemberName":null,"collectionTagObjs":[],"notificationTitle":null,"minimizedStoryCount":null,"shortId":"e90244a5704bc4e50514e29a4c7389f8","allowAd":true,"layoutType":"Small Photo","pollWeek":null,"disclaimerText":null,"teams":null,"hubPeekTagName":null,"sponsorAttribution":null,"bracketsSettings":null,"textScale":null,"expandedStoryCount":null,"hubPeekTagId":null,"cardHeadline":null,"id":"urn:publicid:ap.org:e90244a5704bc4e50514e29a4c7389f8","pollId":null,"contents":[{"embedHeight":null,"contentSponsor":null,"mediumIds":["5dead14a84b047d88cd6519f8b81f86f","262764e9b72c455da5