d to 25 % of whites. Similarly, almost half of black people questioned (47%) said they were following stories about local hospitals closely, while a quarter of whites (24%) said the same thing.\u003c/p>\u003cdiv class=\"ad-placeholder\">\u003c/div>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>Roughly half of blacks had an intense interest in the number of COVID-19 cases and deaths, with 34% of whites saying the same thing.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>“The differences in these data are particularly striking,” said Amy Mitchell, director of journalism research at Pew.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>According to current CDC death statistics, 23% of the Americans who have died from COVID-19 deaths were black, though blacks make up only about 13% of the U.S. population. About 53% of COVID-19 fatalities were white, though whites make up about 60% of the U.S. population\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>\u003cp>The margin of error in Pew's American News Pathways Project is plus or minus 1.5%.\u003c/p>\u003cp>\n\u003c/p>","mediaCount":0,"shortId":"7263794ba493abca70c6d54e3062ca49","localLinkUrl":"https://apnews.com/7263794ba493abca70c6d54e3062ca49","interactiveLinkUrl":null,"downloadSettings":null,"interactiveLinkUrlText":null,"richEmbeds":[],"id":"urn:publicid:ap.org:7263794ba493abca70c6d54e3062ca49","media":[],"videoContext":null,"tagIds":["apf-usnews","Raceandethnicity","UnderstandingtheOutbreak","apf-Health","apf-entertainment","apf-lifestyle","VirusOutbreak"],"hasTextOverlay":false,"bylines":null,"leadPhotoId":null}],"notificationUrl":null,"textColor":null,"sponsorUrl":null,"teamLimit":null,"cardType":"Wire Story","sponsorServeAd":false,"notificationText":null,"notificationUpdated":null},{"feed":[],"pollUpdated":null,"headlineWidget":null,"dividerColor":"#000000","tagObjs":[],"sponsorImageUrl":null,"hubPeekLinkText":null,"borderColor":null,"cardTitle":null,"localMemberName":null,"collectionTagObjs":[],"notificationTitle":null,"minimizedStoryCount":null,"shortId":"1e0660c22b3202c211ad